05002nam a22006015i 9780822392774DE-B159720201028084219.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201028t20102010ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223927747 a10.1515/97808223927742doi  a(DE-B1597)553282  a(OCoLC)636959164  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aHT147.C48bV57 2010 7aHIS0080002bisacsh04a307.760951/0905222  aMS 12602rvk0(DE-625)rvk/123582:1 aVisser, Robin, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCities Surround The Countryside :bUrban Aesthetics in Postsocialist China /cRobin Visser. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2010] 4cÂ©2010  a1 online resource (373 p.) :b53 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction Cities Surround the Countryside -- t1. Designing the Postsocialist City Urban Planning and Its Discontents -- t2. Theorizing the Postsocialist City The Cultural Politics of Urban Aesthetics -- t3. Performing the Postsocialist City Beijing Identity in Art, Cinema, and Fiction -- t4 Consuming the Postsocialist City Shanghai Identity in Art, Cinema, and Fiction -- t5 The Melancholic Urban Subject Black Snow, Private Life, Breathing, and Candy -- t6 Postsocialist Urban Ethics Modernity and the Morality of Everyday Life -- tConclusion. Sustainable Chinese Aesthetics -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDenounced as parasitical under Chairman Mao and devalued by the norms of traditional Chinese ethics, the city now functions as a site of individual and collective identity in China. Cities envelop the countryside, not only geographically and demographically but also in terms of cultural impact. Robin Visser illuminates the cultural dynamics of three decades of radical urban development in China. Interpreting fiction, cinema, visual art, architecture, and urban design, she analyzes how the aesthetics of the urban environment have shaped the emotions and behavior of people and cultures, and how individual and collective images of and practices in the city have produced urban aesthetics. By relating the built environment to culture, Visser situates postsocialist Chinese urban aesthetics within local and global economic and intellectual trends.In the 1980s, writers, filmmakers, and artists began to probe the contradictions in China's urbanization policies and rhetoric. Powerful neorealist fiction, cinema, documentaries, paintings, photographs, performances, and installations contrasted forms of glittering urban renewal with the government's inattention to a livable urban infrastructure. Narratives and images depicting the melancholy urban subject came to illustrate ethical quandaries raised by urban life. Visser relates her analysis of this art to major transformations in urban planning under global neoliberalism, to the development of cultural studies in the Chinese academy, and to ways that specific cities, particularly Beijing and Shanghai, figure in the cultural imagination. Despite the environmental and cultural destruction caused by China's neoliberal policies, Visser argues for the emergence of a new urban self-awareness, one that offers creative resolutions for the dilemmas of urbanism through new forms of intellectual engagement in society and nascent forms of civic governance.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Okt 2020) 0aAestheticsxElectronic books. 0aAesthetics. 0aCities and townsxHistoryx21st centuryxChina. 0aCities and townszChinaxHistoryy21st century. 0aCity and town lifexHistoryx21st centuryxChina. 0aCity and town lifezChinaxHistoryy21st century. 7aHISTORY / Asia / China.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook pa